# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: active-transport
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:active-transport/academy-of-sciences-of-the-czech-republic] The **Czech Academy of Sciences** (abbr.
[src:active-transport/academy-of-sciences-of-the-czech-republic] **CAS**, Czech: *Akademie věd České republiky*, abbr.
[src:active-transport/academy-of-sciences-of-the-czech-republic] The academy is the leading non-university public research institution in the Czech Republic.
[src:active-transport/academy-of-sciences-of-the-czech-republic] It conducts both fundamental and strategic applied research.
[src:active-transport/academy-of-sciences-of-the-czech-republic] It has three scientific divisions, namely the Division of Mathematics, Physics, and Earth Sciences, Division of Chemical and Life Sciences, and Division of Humanities and Social Sciences.
[src:active-transport/academy-of-sciences-of-the-czech-republic] The academy currently manages a network of sixty research institutes and five supporting units staffed by a total of 6,400 employees, over one half of whom are university-trained researchers and Ph.D. scientists.
[src:active-transport/academy-of-sciences-of-the-czech-republic] The Head Office of the academy and forty research institutes are located in Prague, the remaining institutes being situated throughout the country.
[src:active-transport/academy-of-sciences-of-the-czech-republic] In 2010, the academy adopted an open access policy to make its research outputs free to read and reuse.
[src:active-transport/academy-of-sciences-of-the-czech-republic] The official structure of the CAS consists of three areas (sciences about inanimate nature, life sciences, and humanities), each with three sections.
[src:active-transport/academy-of-sciences-of-the-czech-republic] Each of these 9 sections contains between 4 and 8 institutes.
[src:active-transport/academy-of-sciences-of-the-czech-republic] An institute is divided further into departments, laboratories, or working teams, depending on the size and the topic of the institute.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Public policies promoting active mobility tend to improve health indicators by increasing the levels of physical fitness and reducing the rates of obesity and diabetes, whilst also reducing the consumption of fossil fuels and consequent carbon emissions.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] These policies are proven to result in large increases in active transportation for commuting: for example Portland, Oregon, was able to increase bicycle use 5-fold from 1990 to 2009 with pro-cycling programs.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Studies have shown that city level programs are more effective than encouraging active mobility on the individual level.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Health benefits of active mobility include alleviating urban pressures, reduced energy consumption and production, and improved quality of life.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Commonly active transport prevents the chances of fatal disease rooted from pollution and environmental issues.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Active mobility improves health by decreasing air pollution from cars.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] However, negative health problems can arise from inactive and sedentary lifestyles.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The US Centers for Disease Control recommends increasing access to active transportation.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Multiple U.S. studies advocate for increased access to active transportation for everyone, including children, due to multiple health benefits.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Sedentary people can lower their BMI by increasing physical activity.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] A House of Commons of the United Kingdom Health Committee report about Obesity in 2004 recommended cycling and walking as key components to combat obesity.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Public Health England estimated in 2016 that in the UK, physical inactivity directly contributes to one in six deaths every year.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The PHE report notes that walking and cycling daily is effective to increase physical activity and reduce levels of obesity, as well as prevent cardiovascular disease, type 2 diabetes, cancer and several mental illnesses, including depression.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Physical exercise improves mental and physical health.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Cyclists and walkers perceive their environment differently than people driving in cars because cars block sensory inputs that active mobility exposes.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Proponents of active mobility assert that activities like cycling and walking promote a feeling of community and connection, improving mental health and overall wellbeing.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Providing good infrastructure for active mobility effectively promotes this type of transportation to decrease traffic and urban congestion.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Cycling and walking can save money by reducing money spent on gasoline.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Consequences of cycling and walking include increased exposure to air pollution, noise, and more frequent accidents.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Cycling reduces the need for large roads and parking lots as bikes occupy 8% of available space compared to cars.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] As cycling and walking increases, urban infrastructure can be transformed to parks to add green space to urban environments.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Aesthetically pleasing areas can become optimal places for walking and cycling in cities.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Urban environments can also be transformed into walkable areas, which can benefit the elderly, but safety can be problematic if areas are congested with cars.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Designing safe walkable areas in cities can increase the popularity of walking, decrease physical inactivity, and improve health.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Additionally, electric bike users benefit from this type of physical activity.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] In seven European cities, electric bike users had 10% higher weekly energy expenditure than other cyclists.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] People switching to e-bike from either private cars or public transport expend more energy as physical activity increases, gaining between 550 and 880 Metabolic Equivalent Task minutes per week.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Electric bikes may act as a cycling enabler for women.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] An environmental benefit of active mobility is reducing greenhouse gas emissions to slow global warming.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Every year, a typical car emits 4.6 metric tons of carbon dioxide.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] As a greenhouse gas, carbon dioxide in the atmosphere speeds up the effects of climate change.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] As automobile use increases greenhouse gas emissions, the rates in which our Earth is reaching climate tipping point thresholds are escalating.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Active mobility lowers daily greenhouse gas emissions, slowing these tipping points.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] For example, in New Zealand, active mobility has been found to reduce emissions of carbon dioxide by 1% annually.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] In a study of 7 European cities, it was found that individual changes in active travel come with significant lifecycle carbon emissions benefits, even in European urban contexts with already high walking and cycling shares.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] An increase in cycling or walking consistently and independently decreased mobility-related lifecycle CO 2 emissions.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] An average person cycling 1 trip/day more and driving 1 trip/day less for 200 days a year would decrease mobility-related lifecycle CO 2 emissions by about 0.5 tonnes over a year.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Air and noise pollution are negative effects of vehicular transport.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Air pollution negatively affects human health and the environment.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Air pollution can cause acid rain, eutrophication, haze, wildlife deaths, thinning of Earth's ozone layer, crop damage, and global climate change.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Noise pollution disrupts ecosystems and wildlife.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Active mobility reduces air and noise pollution by substituting for cars that produce greenhouse gases and noise, benefiting the environment and urban ecosystems.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Active mobility has appealed to policymakers because of its beneficial contributions to physical health and reductions of air pollution, leading to legislative efforts to make cycling and walking safer and more attractive for commuting and personal errands.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] These measures include infrastructure changes to accommodate more cyclists and pedestrians on roads, regulations to limit car traffic, and education and training to improve the coordination between motor vehicles and individuals using active mobility.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Infrastructure developments that have been correlated with increased active mobility are wider sidewalks, street lighting, flat terrain, and urban greenery, particularly with access to parks.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Several researchers have also emphasized that the largest contribution to active mobility comes from easy access to local amenities such as restaurants, shops, and theaters, which can be promoted by local governments.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] A significant concern about increased active mobility is a corresponding increase in injuries and deaths, especially between pedestrians or cyclists and motor vehicles.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Active mobility may often be more time-consuming than commuting by vehicle, and the effects of distance, geographic features such as hills, and climate may make outdoor exertion uncomfortable or impractical.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Another criticism of active transportation policy contends that converting traffic lanes for bicycle use makes travel more difficult for commuters who must a motor vehicle.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The European Union's Mobility and Transport organization includes the promotion of walking and cycling among its strategies to enable more sustainable transportation in Europe.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The European Union has also adopted a Vision Zero goal to eliminate all traffic deaths, seeking to mitigate the number of incidents between pedestrians and cyclists and motor vehicles, as these commonly result in serious injury or death.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Separate from the European Union, several European cities and regions founded an organization, Polis, in 1989 to coordinate efforts between local governments and the European Union to improve the efficiency of transportation.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] This includes the facilitation of active mobility, which Polis states provides benefits to the environment and to the public's physical health and asserts that these improvements contribute to the economy as well.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Polis recommends that policy decisions should account for benefits from reduced health and environmental costs from active mobility, increased city accessibility from reduced congestion and pollution, and consider regulations on vehicle design to address concerns of safety and convenience.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Polis encourages the development of Sustainable Urban Mobility Plans (SUMPs) to guide mobility projects in cities of all sizes.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Active mobility is used widely in the Netherlands, comprising more than 40% of commuting in urban areas.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The flat topography and temperate climate of the Netherlands benefits active mobility, which has been supported by government policy for decades, including 35,000 kilometers of dedicated cycling paths.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] As a result, the Dutch government estimates that there are about 1.3 bikes per person in the Netherlands.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] A consequence of this is that about 20% of Dutch road accident fatalities are cyclists, with more than 100 cyclists perishing each year.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] This rate and number are higher than most other European countries, reflecting the high use of active mobility in the Netherlands.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] However, policy efforts by the Ministry of Industry and Water Management may have contributed to a declining mortality rate, which fell more than 30% from 2007 to 2016.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The Land Transport Authority (LTA) of Singapore pursues a stated goal to supplement mechanized transportation methods with "walk and cycle options".
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Following a test plan implemented in the neighborhood of Tampines, the Minister of Transport presented a National Cycling Plan in 2013 to provide paths to integrate cycling with Singapore's extensive Mass Rapid Transit system.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] This includes 190 kilometers of paths, thousands of bicycle parking racks, signage, and cyclist education.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] These efforts have been criticized, however, as being limited in scope, especially for limiting the expansion of cycling access to off-road connections, such as through the Park Connectors Network, rather than more infrastructure for commuting in cities.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The UK Government's plan for active travel in England was released in 2020 and is known as *Gear Change*.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The plan aims to make England a 'great cycling nation'.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The plan aims to create cycling and walking corridors, introduce more low-traffic neighbourhoods and school streets, aims to set high standards for cycling infrastructure.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The plan accompanies £2 billion in additional funding over the following five years for cycling and walking announced in May 2020.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The plan also introduced a new body and inspectorate known as Active Travel England.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Scottish Government policy aims to increase the use of active travel modes in Scotland for shorter journeys and to make active mobility safer and inclusive.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The National Walking Strategy was published in 2017 and the Cycling Action Plan for Scotland (CAPS) was last updated in 2017.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The active travel advocacy group Cycling UK criticised the Scottish Government for not increasing funding for active travel.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The Scottish budget allocates £100 million for cycling and walking, which is 3.3% of the transport budget or the total cost of three miles of the A9 dualling scheme.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Within the public sector in Scotland the transport sector has the lowest percentage of women in senior posts.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Only 6.25% of heads of transport bodies are women.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Other steps include the *Active Travel (Wales) Act 2013,* which passed in 2013.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The act requires local authorities to continuously improve facilities and routes for pedestrians and cyclists and to prepare maps identifying current and potential future routes for their use.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] It also requires road improvement and development projects to consider the needs of pedestrians and cyclists at the design stage.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Residents of the United States use active mobility as a mode of transportation less often than residents of other countries.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The far greater mortality rates of pedestrians and cyclists in U.S. cities has been cited as a contributing factor to this trend.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Efforts to increase use of active mobility have been undertaken at the federal levels by the U.S.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Department of Transportation, which pursues the development of active commuting through its Livability Initiative.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Funding increases for these programs, such as the Fixing America's Surface Transportation (FAST) act of 2015, have garnered bipartisan support.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Multiple cities in the United States, including Seattle, Chicago, Minneapolis, Sacramento, and Houston, have implemented their own policies to encourage the active mobility for commuting to work and to school.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] More extensive efforts involve detailed active transportation programs (ATPs), such as those implemented in California, Portland, Oregon, Fort Worth, Texas, and San Diego County.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] However, these efforts have struggled to promote measurable changes in the percentage of commuters using active transportation to work: in the United States Census Bureau's American Community Survey, 3.4% of Americans biked or walked to work in 2013, and only 3.1% did so in 2018.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] People with disabilities often face more issues with active transport than those without disabilities.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Some people have medical barriers to active travel.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] There are some instances where it is not possible for a person to walk or cycle, and, even if the physical, societal and financial barriers were removed, some would still need access to a motor vehicle.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] For those who wish to cycle, barriers can include narrow cycle lanes, infrastructure that requires a cyclist to dismount, physical access barriers and a lack of suitable cycle parking facilities.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] In some cities and countries women lead the way when it comes to walking.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] 54% of journeys completed wholly on foot in London are made by women.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] According to research into gender differences in active travel across a range of international cities, women are more likely than men to walk and more likely to use public transport.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] The gender differences in active travel metrics are age dependent.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Women's and men's perception of danger and safety offer differential travel experience.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Research highlights the importance of a gendered approach towards healthy living and active transport policy making with considerations for reducing road traffic danger and male violence.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Men are more likely to have access to private cars than women.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Design that benefits cars over other modes of transport disproportionately benefits men.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Men and women tend to have different patterns of journeys.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Women are more likely to be trip chaining, and trip chaining encourages car use.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] Women are also more likely to be 'encumbered' by carrying children, shopping or accompanied by elderly companions In the UK fewer women cycle than men and road safety is cited as a concern relating to cycling and to walking.
[src:active-transport/active-mobility] A Sustrans report in the UK found a lack of evidence that women participate in creating transport policy and planning.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In cellular biology, **active transport** is the movement of molecules or ions across a cell membrane from a region of lower concentration to a region of higher concentration—against the concentration gradient.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Active transport requires cellular energy to achieve this movement.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] There are two types of active transport: **primary active transport** that uses adenosine triphosphate (ATP), and **secondary active transport** that uses an electrochemical gradient.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] This process is in contrast to passive transport, which allows molecules or ions to move down their concentration gradient, from an area of high concentration to an area of low concentration, without using energy.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Active transport is essential for various physiological processes, such as nutrient uptake, hormone secretion, and impulse transmission.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] For example, the sodium–potassium pump uses ATP to pump sodium ions out of the cell and potassium ions into the cell, maintaining a concentration gradient essential for cellular function.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Active transport is highly selective and regulated, with different transporters specific to different molecules or ions.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Dysregulation of active transport can lead to various disorders, including cystic fibrosis, caused by a malfunctioning chloride channel, and diabetes, resulting from defects in glucose transport into cells.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Unlike passive transport, which uses the kinetic energy and natural entropy of molecules moving down a gradient, active transport uses cellular energy to move them against a gradient, polar repulsion, or other resistance.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Active transport is usually associated with accumulating high concentrations of molecules that the cell needs, such as ions, glucose and amino acids.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Examples of active transport include the uptake of glucose in the intestines in humans and the uptake of mineral ions into root hair cells of plants.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In 1848, the German physiologist Emil du Bois-Reymond suggested the possibility of active transport of substances across membranes.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In 1926, Dennis Robert Hoagland investigated the ability of plants to absorb salts against a concentration gradient and discovered the dependence of nutrient absorption and translocation on metabolic energy using innovative model systems under controlled experimental conditions.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Rosenberg (1948) formulated the concept of active transport based on energetic considerations, but later it would be redefined.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In 1997, Jens Christian Skou, a Danish physician received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his research regarding the sodium-potassium pump.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] One category of cotransporters that is especially prominent in research regarding diabetes treatment is sodium-glucose cotransporters.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] These transporters were discovered by scientists at the National Health Institute.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] These scientists had noticed a discrepancy in the absorption of glucose at different points in the kidney tubule of a rat.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] The gene was then discovered for intestinal glucose transport protein and linked to these membrane sodium glucose cotransport systems.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] The first of these membrane transport proteins was named SGLT1 followed by the discovery of SGLT2.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Robert Krane also played a prominent role in this field.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] There are two forms of active transport, primary active transport and secondary active transport.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In primary active transport, the proteins involved are pumps that normally use chemical energy in the form of ATP.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Secondary active transport, however, makes use of potential energy, which is usually derived through exploitation of an electrochemical gradient.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] The energy created from one ion moving down its electrochemical gradient is used to power the transport of another ion moving against its electrochemical gradient.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] This involves pore-forming proteins that form channels across the cell membrane.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In an antiporter, one substrate is transported in one direction across the membrane while another is cotransported in the opposite direction.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In a symporter, two substrates are transported in the same direction across the membrane.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Antiport and symport processes are associated with secondary active transport, meaning that one of the two substances is transported against its concentration gradient, utilizing the energy derived from the transport of another ion (mostly Na+, K+ or H+ ions) down its concentration gradient.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] If substrate molecules are moving from areas of lower concentration to areas of higher concentration (i.e., in the opposite direction as, or *against* the concentration gradient), specific transmembrane carrier proteins are required.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] These proteins have receptors that bind to specific molecules (e.g., glucose) and transport them across the cell membrane.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Because energy is required in this process, it is known as 'active' transport.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Examples of active transport include the transportation of sodium out of the cell and potassium into the cell by the sodium-potassium pump.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Active transport often takes place in the internal lining of the small intestine.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Plants need to absorb mineral salts from the soil or other sources, but these salts exist in very dilute solution.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Active transport enables these cells to take up salts from this dilute solution against the direction of the concentration gradient.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] For example, chloride (Cl−) and nitrate (NO3−) ions exist in the cytosol of plant cells, and need to be transported into the vacuole.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] While the vacuole has channels for these ions, transportation of them is against the concentration gradient, and thus movement of these ions is driven by hydrogen pumps, or proton pumps.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Primary active transport, also called direct active transport, directly uses metabolic energy to transport molecules across a membrane.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Substances that are transported across the cell membrane by primary active transport include metal ions, such as Na+, K+, Mg2+, and Ca2+.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] These charged particles require ion pumps or ion channels to cross membranes and distribute through the body.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Most of the enzymes that perform this type of transport are transmembrane ATPases.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] A primary ATPase universal to all animal life is the sodium-potassium pump, which helps to maintain the cell potential.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] The sodium-potassium pump maintains the membrane potential by moving three Na+ ions out of the cell for every two K+ ions moved into the cell.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Other sources of energy for primary active transport are redox energy and photon energy (light).
[src:active-transport/active-transport] An example of primary active transport using redox energy is the mitochondrial electron transport chain that uses the reduction energy of NADH to move protons across the inner mitochondrial membrane against their concentration gradient.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] An example of primary active transport using light energy are the proteins involved in photosynthesis that use the energy of photons to create a proton gradient across the thylakoid membrane and also to create reduction power in the form of NADPH.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] ATP hydrolysis is used to transport hydrogen ions against the electrochemical gradient (from low to high hydrogen ion concentration).
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Phosphorylation of the carrier protein and the binding of a hydrogen ion induce a conformational (shape) change that drives the hydrogen ions to transport against the electrochemical gradient.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Hydrolysis of the bound phosphate group and release of hydrogen ion then restores the carrier to its original conformation.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] ABC (ATP binding cassette) transporter: MDR, CFTR, etc.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Adenosine triphosphate-binding cassette transporters (ABC transporters) comprise a large and diverse protein family, often functioning as ATP-driven pumps.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Usually, there are several domains involved in the overall transporter protein's structure, including two nucleotide-binding domains that constitute the ATP-binding motif and two hydrophobic transmembrane domains that create the "pore" component.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In broad terms, ABC transporters are involved in the import or export of molecules across a cell membrane; yet within the protein family there is an extensive range of function.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In plants, ABC transporters are often found within cell and organelle membranes, such as the mitochondria, chloroplast, and plasma membrane.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] There is evidence to support that plant ABC transporters play a direct role in pathogen response, phytohormone transport, and detoxification.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Furthermore, certain plant ABC transporters may function in actively exporting volatile compounds and antimicrobial metabolites.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In petunia flowers (*Petunia hybrida*), the ABC transporter PhABCG1 is involved in the active transport of volatile organic compounds.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] PhABCG1 is expressed in the petals of open flowers.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In general, volatile compounds may promote the attraction of seed-dispersal organisms and pollinators, as well as aid in defense, signaling, allelopathy, and protection.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] To study the protein PhABCG1, transgenic petunia RNA interference lines were created with decreased *PhABCG1* expression levels.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In these transgenic lines, a decrease in emission of volatile compounds was observed.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Thus, PhABCG1 is likely involved in the export of volatile compounds.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Subsequent experiments involved incubating control and transgenic lines that expressed *PhABCG1* to test for transport activity involving different substrates.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Ultimately, PhABCG1 is responsible for the protein-mediated transport of volatile organic compounds, such as benzyl alcohol and methylbenzoate, across the plasma membrane.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Additionally in plants, ABC transporters may be involved in the transport of cellular metabolites.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Pleiotropic Drug Resistance ABC transporters are hypothesized to be involved in stress response and export antimicrobial metabolites.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] One example of this type of ABC transporter is the protein NtPDR1.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] This unique ABC transporter is found in *Nicotiana tabacum* BY2 cells and is expressed in the presence of microbial elicitors.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] NtPDR1 is localized in the root epidermis and aerial trichomes of the plant.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Experiments using antibodies specifically targeting NtPDR1 followed by Western blotting allowed for this determination of localization.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Furthermore, it is likely that the protein NtPDR1 actively transports out antimicrobial diterpene molecules, which are toxic to the cell at high levels.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In secondary active transport, also known as cotransport or coupled transport, energy is used to transport molecules across a membrane; however, in contrast to primary active transport, there is no direct coupling of ATP.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Instead, it relies upon the electrochemical potential difference created by pumping ions in/out of the cell.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Permitting one ion or molecule to move down an electrochemical gradient, but possibly against the concentration gradient where it is more concentrated to that where it is less concentrated, increases entropy and can serve as a source of energy for metabolism (e.g. in ATP synthase).
[src:active-transport/active-transport] The energy derived from the pumping of protons across a cell membrane is frequently used as the energy source in secondary active transport.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In humans, sodium (Na+) is a commonly cotransported ion across the plasma membrane, whose electrochemical gradient is then used to power the active transport of a second ion or molecule against its gradient.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In bacteria and small yeast cells, a commonly cotransported ion is hydrogen.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Hydrogen pumps are also used to create an electrochemical gradient to carry out processes within cells such as in the electron transport chain, an important function of cellular respiration that happens in the mitochondrion of the cell.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Crane presented for the first time his discovery of the sodium-glucose cotransport as the mechanism for intestinal glucose absorption.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Crane's discovery of cotransport was the first ever proposal of flux coupling in biology.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Cotransporters can be classified as symporters and antiporters depending on whether the substances move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In an antiporter two species of ions or other solutes are pumped in opposite directions across a membrane.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] One of these species is allowed to flow from high to low concentration, which yields the entropic energy to drive the transport of the other solute from a low concentration region to a high one.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] An example is the sodium-calcium exchanger or antiporter, which allows three sodium ions into the cell to transport one calcium out.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] This antiporter mechanism is important within the membranes of cardiac muscle cells in order to keep the calcium concentration in the cytoplasm low.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Many cells also possess calcium ATPases, which can operate at lower intracellular concentrations of calcium and sets the normal or resting concentration of this important second messenger.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] But the ATPase exports calcium ions more slowly: only 30 per second versus 2000 per second by the exchanger.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] The exchanger comes into service when the calcium concentration rises steeply or "spikes" and enables rapid recovery.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] This shows that a single type of ion can be transported by several enzymes, which need not be active all the time (constitutively), but may exist to meet specific, intermittent needs.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] A symporter uses the downhill movement of one solute species from high to low concentration to move another molecule uphill from low concentration to high concentration (against its concentration gradient).
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Both molecules are transported in the same direction.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] An example is the glucose symporter SGLT1, which co-transports one glucose (or galactose) molecule into the cell for every two sodium ions it imports into the cell.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] This symporter is located in the small intestines, heart, and brain.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] It is also located in the S3 segment of the proximal tubule in each nephron in the kidneys.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Its mechanism is exploited in glucose rehydration therapy This mechanism uses the absorption of sugar through the walls of the intestine to pull water in along with it.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Defects in SGLT2 prevent effective reabsorption of glucose, causing familial renal glucosuria.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Endocytosis and exocytosis are both forms of active transport that move materials into and out of cells, respectively, via vesicles.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] In the case of endocytosis, the cellular membrane folds around the desired materials outside the cell.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] The ingested particle becomes trapped within a pouch, known as a vesicle, inside the cytoplasm.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Often enzymes from lysosomes are then used to digest the molecules absorbed by this process.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Substances that enter the cell via signal mediated electrolysis include proteins, hormones and growth and stabilization factors.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Viruses enter cells through a form of endocytosis that involves their outer membrane fusing with the membrane of the cell.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] This forces the viral DNA into the host cell.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Biologists distinguish two main types of endocytosis: pinocytosis and phagocytosis.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] Exocytosis involves the removal of substances through the fusion of the outer cell membrane and a vesicle membrane.
[src:active-transport/active-transport] An example of exocytosis would be the transmission of neurotransmitters across a synapse between brain cells.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The **ABC transporters**, **ATP synthase (ATP)-binding cassette transporters** are a transport system superfamily that is one of the largest and possibly one of the oldest gene families.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It is represented in all extant phyla, from prokaryotes to humans.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABC transporters belong to translocases.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABC transporters often consist of multiple subunits, one or two of which are transmembrane proteins and one or two of which are membrane-associated AAA ATPases.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The ATPase subunits utilize the energy of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) binding and hydrolysis to provide the energy needed for the translocation of substrates across membranes, either for uptake or for export of the substrate.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Most of the uptake systems also have an extracytoplasmic receptor, a solute binding protein.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Some homologous ATPases function in non-transport-related processes such as translation of RNA and DNA repair.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Like the ABC exporters, it is possible that the integral membrane proteins of ABC uptake systems also evolved at least three times independently, based on their high resolution three-dimensional structures.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABC uptake porters take up a large variety of nutrients, biosynthetic precursors, trace metals and vitamins, while exporters transport lipids, sterols, drugs, and a large variety of primary and secondary metabolites.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Some of these exporters in humans are involved in tumor resistance, cystic fibrosis and a range of other inherited human diseases.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] High level expression of the genes encoding some of these exporters in both prokaryotic and eukaryotic organisms (including human) result in the development of resistance to multiple drugs such as antibiotics and anti-cancer agents.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Hundreds of ABC transporters have been characterized from both prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABC genes are essential for many processes in the cell, and mutations in human genes cause or contribute to several human genetic diseases.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Forty eight ABC genes have been reported in humans.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABC transporters are also involved in multiple drug resistance, and this is how some of them were first identified.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] When the ABC transport proteins are overexpressed in cancer cells, they can export anticancer drugs and render tumors resistant.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABC transporters utilize the energy of ATP binding and hydrolysis to transport various substrates across cellular membranes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] They are divided into three main functional categories.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In prokaryotes, *importers* mediate the uptake of nutrients into the cell.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The substrates that can be transported include ions, amino acids, peptides, sugars, and other molecules that are mostly hydrophilic.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The membrane-spanning region of the ABC transporter protects hydrophilic substrates from the lipids of the membrane bilayer thus providing a pathway across the cell membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Eukaryotes do not possess any importers.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] *Exporters* or *effluxers*, which are present both in prokaryotes and eukaryotes, function as pumps that extrude toxins and drugs out of the cell.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In gram-negative bacteria, exporters transport lipids and some polysaccharides from the cytoplasm to the periplasm.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The third subgroup of ABC proteins do not function as transporters, but are rather involved in translation and DNA repair processes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Bacterial ABC transporters are essential in cell viability, virulence, and pathogenicity.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Iron ABC uptake systems, for example, are important effectors of virulence.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Pathogens use siderophores, such as Enterobactin, to scavenge iron that is in complex with high-affinity iron-binding proteins or erythrocytes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] These are high-affinity iron-chelating molecules that are secreted by bacteria and reabsorb iron into iron-siderophore complexes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The chvE-gguAB gene in *Agrobacterium tumefaciens* encodes glucose and galactose importers that are also associated with virulence.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Transporters are extremely vital in cell survival such that they function as protein systems that counteract any undesirable change occurring in the cell.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] For instance, a potential lethal increase in osmotic strength is counterbalanced by activation of osmosensing ABC transporters that mediate uptake of solutes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Other than functioning in transport, some bacterial ABC proteins are also involved in the regulation of several physiological processes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] They also play important roles in biosynthetic pathways, including extracellular polysaccharide biosynthesis and cytochrome biogenesis.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Although most eukaryotic ABC transporters are effluxers, some are not directly involved in transporting substrates.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In the cystic fibrosis transmembrane regulator (CFTR) and in the sulfonylurea receptor (SUR), ATP hydrolysis is associated with the regulation of opening and closing of ion channels carried by the ABC protein itself or other proteins.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Human ABC transporters are involved in several diseases that arise from polymorphisms in ABC genes and rarely due to complete loss of function of single ABC proteins.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The human ABCB (MDR/TAP) family is responsible for multiple drug resistance (MDR) against a variety of structurally unrelated drugs.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABCB1 or MDR1 P-glycoprotein is also involved in other biological processes for which lipid transport is the main function.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It is found to mediate the secretion of the steroid aldosterone by the adrenals, and its inhibition blocked the migration of dendritic immune cells, possibly related to the outward transport of the lipid platelet activating factor (PAF).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It has also been reported that ABCB1 mediates transport of cortisol and dexamethasone, but not of progesterone in ABCB1 transfected cells.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] MDR1 can also transport cholesterol, short-chain and long-chain analogs of phosphatidylcholine (PC), phosphatidylethanolamine (PE), phosphatidylserine (PS), sphingomyelin (SM), and glucosylceramide (GlcCer).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Multispecific transport of diverse endogenous lipids through the MDR1 transporter can possibly affect the transbilayer distribution of lipids, in particular of species normally predominant on the inner plasma membrane leaflet such as PS and PE.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] More recently, ABC-transporters have been shown to exist within the placenta, indicating they could play a protective role for the developing fetus against xenobiotics.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Evidence has shown that placental expression of the ABC-transporters P-glycoprotein (P-gp) and breast cancer resistance protein (BCRP) are increased in preterm compared to term placentae, with P-gp expression further increased in preterm pregnancies with chorioamnionitis.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] To a lesser extent, increasing maternal BMI also associated with increased placental ABC-transporter expression, but only at preterm.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] All ABC transport proteins share a structural organization consisting of four core domains.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] These domains consist of two trans-membrane (T) domains and two cytosolic (A) domains.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The two T domains alternate between an inward and outward facing orientation, and the alternation is powered by the hydrolysis of adenosine triphosphate or ATP.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ATP binds to the A subunits and it is then hydrolyzed to power the alternation, but the exact process by which this happens is not known.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The four domains can be present in four separate polypeptides, which occur mostly in bacteria, or present in one or two multi-domain polypeptides.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] When the polypeptides are one domain, they can be referred to as a full domain, and when they are two multi-domains they can be referred to as a half domain.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The T domains are each built of typically 10 membrane spanning alpha helices, through which the transported substance can cross through the plasma membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Also, the structure of the T domains determines the specificity of each ABC protein.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In the inward facing conformation, the binding site on the A domain is open directly to the surrounding aqueous solutions.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This allows hydrophilic molecules to enter the binding site directly from the inner leaflet of the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In addition, a gap in the protein is accessible directly from the hydrophobic core of the inner leaflet of the membrane bilayer.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This allows hydrophobic molecules to enter the binding site directly from the inner leaflet of the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] After the ATP powered move to the outward facing conformation, molecules are released from the binding site and allowed to escape into the exoplasmic leaflet or directly into the extracellular medium.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The common feature of all ABC transporters is that they consist of two distinct domains, the *transmembrane domain (TMD)* and the *nucleotide-binding domain (NBD)*.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The TMD, also known as membrane-spanning domain (MSD) or integral membrane (IM) domain, consists of alpha helices, embedded in the membrane bilayer.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It recognizes a variety of substrates and undergoes conformational changes to transport the substrate across the membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The sequence and architecture of TMDs is variable, reflecting the chemical diversity of substrates that can be translocated.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The NBD or ATP-binding cassette (ABC) domain, on the other hand, is located in the cytoplasm and has a highly conserved sequence.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In most exporters, the N-terminal transmembrane domain and the C-terminal ABC domains are fused as a single polypeptide chain, arranged as TMD-NBD-TMD-NBD.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] An example is the *E. coli* hemolysin exporter HlyB.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Importers have an inverted organization, that is, NBD-TMD-NBD-TMD, where the ABC domain is N-terminal whereas the TMD is C-terminal, such as in the *E. coli* MacB protein responsible for macrolide resistance.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The structural architecture of ABC transporters consists minimally of two TMDs and two NBDs.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Four individual polypeptide chains including two TMD and two NBD subunits, may combine to form a *full transporter* such as in the *E. coli* BtuCD importer involved in the uptake of vitamin B12.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Most exporters, such as in the multidrug exporter Sav1866 from *Staphylococcus aureus*, are made up of a homodimer consisting of two *half transporters* or monomers of a TMD fused to a nucleotide-binding domain (NBD).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] A full transporter is often required to gain functionality.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Some ABC transporters have additional elements that contribute to the regulatory function of this class of proteins.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In particular, importers have a high-affinity *binding protein (BP)* that specifically associates with the substrate in the periplasm for delivery to the appropriate ABC transporter.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Exporters do not have the binding protein but have an *intracellular domain (ICD)* that joins the membrane-spanning helices and the ABC domain.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The ICD is believed to be responsible for communication between the TMD and NBD.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Most transporters have transmembrane domains that consist of a total of 12 α-helices with 6 α-helices per monomer.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Since TMDs are structurally diverse, some transporters have varying number of helices (between six and eleven).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The TM domains are categorized into three distinct sets of folds: *type I ABC importer*, *type II ABC importer* and *ABC exporter* folds.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The classification of importer folds is based on detailed characterization of the sequences.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The type I ABC importer fold was originally observed in the ModB TM subunit of the molybdate transporter.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This diagnostic fold can also be found in the MalF and MalG TM subunits of MalFGK2 and the Met transporter MetI.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In the MetI transporter, a minimal set of 5 transmembrane helices constitute this fold while an additional helix is present for both ModB and MalG.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The common organization of the fold is the "up-down" topology of the TM2-5 helices that lines the translocation pathway and the TM1 helix wrapped around the outer, membrane-facing surface and contacts the other TM helices.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The type II ABC importer fold is observed in the twenty TM helix-domain of BtuCD and in Hi1471, a homologous transporter from *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In BtuCD, the packing of the helices is complex.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The noticeable pattern is that the TM2 helix is positioned through the center of the subunit where it is surrounded in close proximity by the other helices.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Meanwhile, the TM5 and TM10 helices are positioned in the TMD interface.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The membrane spanning region of ABC exporters is organized into two "wings" that are composed of helices TM1 and TM2 from one subunit and TM3-6 of the other, in a domain-swapped arrangement.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] A prominent pattern is that helices TM1-3 are related to TM4-6 by an approximate twofold rotation around an axis in the plane of the membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The exporter fold is originally observed in the Sav1866 structure.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It contains 12 TM helices, 6 per monomer.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The ABC domain consists of two domains, the *catalytic core domain* similar to RecA-like motor ATPases and a smaller, structurally diverse *α-helical subdomain* that is unique to ABC transporters.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The larger domain typically consists of two β-sheets and six α helices, where the catalytic *Walker A motif* (GXXGXGKS/T where X is any amino acid) or *P-loop* and *Walker B motif* (ΦΦΦΦD, of which Φ is a hydrophobic residue) is situated.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The helical domain consists of three or four helices and the *ABC signature motif*, also known as *LSGGQ motif*, linker peptide or C motif.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The ABC domain also has a glutamine residue residing in a flexible loop called *Q loop*, lid or γ-phosphate switch, that connects the TMD and ABC.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The Q loop is presumed to be involved in the interaction of the NBD and TMD, particularly in the coupling of nucleotide hydrolysis to the conformational changes of the TMD during substrate translocation.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The *H motif* or switch region contains a highly conserved histidine residue that is also important in the interaction of the ABC domain with ATP.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The name ATP-binding cassette is derived from the diagnostic arrangement of the folds or motifs of this class of proteins upon formation of the ATP sandwich and ATP hydrolysis.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Dimer formation of the two ABC domains of transporters requires ATP binding.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It is generally observed that the ATP bound state is associated with the most extensive interface between ABC domains, whereas the structures of nucleotide-free transporters exhibit conformations with greater separations between the ABC domains.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Structures of the ATP-bound state of isolated NBDs have been reported for importers including HisP, GlcV, MJ1267, *E. coli* MalK (E.c.MalK), *T. litoralis* MalK (TlMalK), and exporters such as TAP, HlyB, MJ0796, Sav1866, and MsbA.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In these transporters, ATP is bound to the ABC domain.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Two molecules of ATP are positioned at the interface of the dimer, sandwiched between the Walker A motif of one subunit and the LSGGQ motif of the other.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This was first observed in Rad50 and reported in structures of MJ0796, the NBD subunit of the LolD transporter from *Methanococcus jannaschii* and E.c.MalK of a maltose transporter.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] These structures were also consistent with results from biochemical studies revealing that ATP is in close contact with residues in the P-loop and LSGGQ motif during catalysis.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Nucleotide binding is required to ensure the electrostatic and/or structural integrity of the active site and contribute to the formation of an active NBD dimer.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In addition, a residue that suggests the tight coupling of ATP binding and dimerization, is the conserved histidine in the H-loop.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This histidine contacts residues across the dimer interface in the Walker A motif and the D loop, a conserved sequence following the Walker B motif.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The enzymatic hydrolysis of ATP requires proper binding of the phosphates and positioning of the γ-phosphate to the attacking water.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In the nucleotide binding site, the oxygen atoms of the β- and γ-phosphates of ATP are stabilized by residues in the Walker A motif and coordinate with Mg2+.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This Mg2+ ion also coordinates with the terminal aspartate residue in the Walker B motif through the attacking H2O.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] A general base, which may be the glutamate residue adjacent to the Walker B motif, glutamine in the Q-loop, or a histidine in the switch region that forms a hydrogen bond with the γ-phosphate of ATP, is found to catalyze the rate of ATP hydrolysis by promoting the attacking H2O.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The precise molecular mechanism of ATP hydrolysis is still controversial.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABC transporters are active transporters, that is, they use energy in the form of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to translocate substrates across cell membranes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] These proteins harness the energy of ATP binding and/or hydrolysis to drive conformational changes in the *transmembrane domain (TMD)* and consequently transport molecules.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABC importers and exporters have a common mechanism for transporting substrates.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The model that describes the conformational changes associated with the binding of the substrate is the *alternating-access model*.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In this model, the substrate binding site alternates between *outward-* and *inward-facing conformations*.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The relative binding affinities of the two conformations for the substrate largely determines the net direction of transport.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] For importers, since translocation is directed from the periplasm to the cytoplasm, the outward-facing conformation has higher binding affinity for the substrate.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In contrast, the substrate binding affinity in exporters is greater in the inward-facing conformation.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] A model that describes the conformational changes in the *nucleotide-binding domain (NBD)* as a result of ATP binding and hydrolysis is the *ATP-switch model*.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This model presents two principal conformations of the NBDs: formation of a closed dimer upon binding two ATP molecules and dissociation to an open dimer facilitated by ATP hydrolysis and release of inorganic phosphate (Pi) and adenosine diphosphate (ADP).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Switching between the open and closed dimer conformations induces conformational changes in the TMD resulting in substrate translocation.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The general mechanism for the transport cycle of ABC transporters has not been fully elucidated, but substantial structural and biochemical data has accumulated to support a model in which ATP binding and hydrolysis is coupled to conformational changes in the transporter.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The resting state of all ABC transporters has the NBDs in an open dimer configuration, with low affinity for ATP.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This open conformation possesses a chamber accessible to the interior of the transporter.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The transport cycle is initiated by binding of substrate to the high-affinity site on the TMDs, which induces conformational changes in the NBDs and enhances the binding of ATP.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Two molecules of ATP bind, cooperatively, to form the closed dimer configuration.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The closed NBD dimer induces a conformational change in the TMDs such that the TMD opens, forming a chamber with an opening opposite to that of the initial state.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The affinity of the substrate to the TMD is reduced, thereby releasing the substrate.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Hydrolysis of ATP follows and then sequential release of Pi and then ADP restores the transporter to its basal configuration.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Although a common mechanism has been suggested, the order of substrate binding, nucleotide binding and hydrolysis, and conformational changes, as well as interactions between the domains is still debated.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Several groups studying ABC transporters have differing assumptions on the driving force of transporter function.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It is generally assumed that ATP hydrolysis provides the principal energy input or "power stroke" for transport and that the NBDs operate alternately and are possibly involved in different steps in the transport cycle.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] However, recent structural and biochemical data shows that ATP binding, rather than ATP hydrolysis, provides the "power stroke".
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Some evidence to show that ATP binding is indeed the power stroke of the transport cycle was reported.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It has been shown that ATP binding induces changes in the substrate-binding properties of the TMDs.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The affinity of ABC transporters for substrates has been difficult to measure directly, and indirect measurements, for instance through stimulation of ATPase activity, often reflects other rate-limiting steps.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Recently, direct measurement of vinblastine binding to permease-glycoprotein (P-glycoprotein) in the presence of nonhydrolyzable ATP analogs, e.g.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] 5'-adenylyl-β-γ-imidodiphosphate (AMP-PNP), showed that ATP binding, in the absence of hydrolysis, is sufficient to reduce substrate-binding affinity.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Also, ATP binding induces substantial conformational changes in the TMDs.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Spectroscopic, protease accessibility and crosslinking studies have shown that ATP binding to the NBDs induces conformational changes in multidrug resistance-associated protein-1 (MRP1), HisPMQ, LmrA, and Pgp.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Two dimensional crystal structures of AMP-PNP-bound Pgp showed that the major conformational change during the transport cycle occurs upon ATP binding and that subsequent ATP hydrolysis introduces more limited changes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Rotation and tilting of transmembrane α-helices may both contribute to these conformational changes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Other studies have focused on confirming that ATP binding induces NBD closed dimer formation.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Biochemical studies of intact transport complexes suggest that the conformational changes in the NBDs are relatively small.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In the absence of ATP, the NBDs may be relatively flexible, but they do not involve a major reorientation of the NBDs with respect to the other domains.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ATP binding induces a rigid body rotation of the two ABC subdomains with respect to each other, which allows the proper alignment of the nucleotide in the active site and interaction with the designated motifs.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] There is strong biochemical evidence that binding of two ATP molecules can be cooperative, that is, ATP must bind to the two active site pockets before the NBDs can dimerize and form the closed, catalytically active conformation.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Most ABC transporters that mediate the uptake of nutrients and other molecules in bacteria rely on a high-affinity solute binding protein (BP).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] BPs are soluble proteins located in the periplasmic space between the inner and outer membranes of gram-negative bacteria.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Gram-positive microorganisms lack a periplasm such that their binding protein is often a lipoprotein bound to the external face of the cell membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Some gram-positive bacteria have BPs fused to the transmembrane domain of the transporter itself.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The first successful x-ray crystal structure of an intact ABC importer is the molybdenum transporter (ModBC-A) from *Archaeoglobus fulgidus*.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Atomic-resolution structures of three other bacterial importers, *E. coli* BtuCD, *E. coli* maltose transporter (MalFGK2-E), and the putative metal-chelate transporter of *Haemophilus influenzae*, HI1470/1, have also been determined.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The structures provided detailed pictures of the interaction of the transmembrane and ABC domains as well as revealed two different conformations with an opening in two opposite directions.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Another common feature of importers is that each NBD is bound to one TMD primarily through a short cytoplasmic helix of the TMD, the "coupling helix".
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This portion of the EAA loop docks in a surface cleft formed between the RecA-like and helical ABC subdomains and lies approximately parallel to the membrane bilayer.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The BtuCD and HI1470/1 are classified as large (Type II) ABC importers.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The transmembrane subunit of the vitamin B12 importer, BtuCD, contains 10 TM helices and the functional unit consists of two copies each of the nucleotide binding domain (NBD) and transmembrane domain (TMD).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The TMD and NBD interact with one another via the cytoplasmic loop between two TM helices and the Q loop in the ABC.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In the absence of nucleotide, the two ABC domains are folded and the dimer interface is open.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] A comparison of the structures with (BtuCDF) and without (BtuCD) binding protein reveals that BtuCD has an opening that faces the periplasm whereas in BtuCDF, the outward-facing conformation is closed to both sides of the membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The structures of BtuCD and the BtuCD homolog, HI1470/1, represent two different conformational states of an ABC transporter.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The predicted translocation pathway in BtuCD is open to the periplasm and closed at the cytoplasmic side of the membrane while that of HI1470/1 faces the opposite direction and open only to the cytoplasm.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The difference in the structures is a 9° twist of one TM subunit relative to the other.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Structures of the ModBC-A and MalFGK2-E, which are in complex with their binding protein, correspond to small (Type I) ABC importers.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The TMDs of ModBC-A and MalFGK2-E have only six helices per subunit.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The homodimer of ModBC-A is in a conformation in which the TM subunits (ModB) orient in an inverted V-shape with a cavity accessible to the cytoplasm.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The ABC subunits (ModC), on the other hand, are arranged in an open, nucleotide-free conformation, in which the P-loop of one subunit faces but is detached from the LSGGQ motif of the other.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The binding protein ModA is in a closed conformation with substrate bound in a cleft between its two lobes and attached to the extracellular loops of ModB, wherein the substrate is sitting directly above the closed entrance of the transporter.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The MalFGK2-E structure resembles the catalytic transition state for ATP hydrolysis.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It is in a closed conformation where it contains two ATP molecules, sandwiched between the Walker A and B motifs of one subunit and the LSGGQ motif of the other subunit.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The maltose binding protein (MBP or MalE) is docked on the periplasmic side of the TM subunits (MalF and MalG) and a large, occluded cavity can be found at the interface of MalF and MalG.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The arrangement of the TM helices is in a conformation that is closed toward the cytoplasm but with an opening that faces outward.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The structure suggests a possibility that MBP may stimulate the ATPase activity of the transporter upon binding.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The mechanism of transport for importers supports the alternating-access model.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The resting state of importers is inward-facing, where the nucleotide binding domain (NBD) dimer interface is held open by the TMDs and facing outward but occluded from the cytoplasm.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Upon docking of the closed, substrate-loaded binding protein towards the periplasmic side of the transmembrane domains, ATP binds and the NBD dimer closes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This switches the resting state of transporter into an outward-facing conformation, in which the TMDs have reoriented to receive substrate from the binding protein.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] After hydrolysis of ATP, the NBD dimer opens and substrate is released into the cytoplasm.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Release of ADP and Pi reverts the transporter into its resting state.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The only inconsistency of this mechanism to the ATP-switch model is that the conformation in its resting, nucleotide-free state is different from the expected outward-facing conformation.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Although that is the case, the key point is that the NBD does not dimerize unless ATP and binding protein is bound to the transporter.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Prokaryotic ABC exporters are abundant and have close homologues in eukaryotes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This class of transporters is studied based on the type of substrate that is transported.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] One class is involved in the protein (e.g. toxins, hydrolytic enzymes, S-layer proteins, lantibiotics, bacteriocins, and competence factors) export and the other in drug efflux.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABC transporters have gained extensive attention because they contribute to the resistance of cells to antibiotics and anticancer agents by pumping drugs out of the cells.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] A common mechanism is the overexpression of ABC exporters like P-glycoprotein (P-gp/ABCB1), multidrug resistance-associated protein 1 (MRP1/ABCC1), and breast cancer resistance protein (BCRP/ABCG2) in cancer cells that limit the exposure to anticancer drugs.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In gram-negative organisms, ABC transporters mediate secretion of protein substrates across inner and outer membranes simultaneously without passing through the periplasm.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This type of secretion is referred to as *type I secretion*, which involves three components that function in concert: an *ABC exporter*, a *membrane fusion protein (MFP)*, and an *outer membrane factor (OMF)*.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] An example is the secretion of hemolysin (HlyA) from *E. coli* where the inner membrane ABC transporter HlyB interacts with an inner membrane fusion protein HlyD and an outer membrane facilitator TolC.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] TolC allows hemolysin to be transported across the two membranes, bypassing the periplasm.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Bacterial drug resistance has become an increasingly major health problem.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] One of the mechanisms for drug resistance is associated with an increase in antibiotic efflux from the bacterial cell.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Drug resistance associated with drug efflux, mediated by P-glycoprotein, was originally reported in mammalian cells.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In bacteria, Levy and colleagues presented the first evidence that antibiotic resistance was caused by active efflux of a drug.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] P-glycoprotein is the best-studied efflux pump and as such has offered important insights into the mechanism of bacterial pumps.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Although some exporters transport a specific type of substrate, most transporters extrude a diverse class of drugs with varying structure.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] These transporters are commonly called multi-drug resistant (MDR) ABC transporters and sometimes referred to as "hydrophobic vacuum cleaners".
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] P-glycoprotein (3.A.1.201.1) is a well-studied protein associated with multi-drug resistance.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It belongs to the human *ABCB (MDR/TAP)* family and is also known as *ABCB1* or *MDR1 Pgp*.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] MDR1 consists of a functional monomer with two transmembrane domains (TMD) and two nucleotide-binding domains (NBD).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This protein can transport mainly cationic or electrically neutral substrates as well as a broad spectrum of amphiphilic substrates.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The structure of the full-size ABCB1 monomer was obtained in the presence and absence of nucleotide using electron cryo crystallography.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Without the nucleotide, the TMDs are approximately parallel and form a barrel surrounding a central pore, with the opening facing towards the extracellular side of the membrane and closed at the intracellular face.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In the presence of the nonhydrolyzable ATP analog, AMP-PNP, the TMDs have a substantial reorganization with three clearly segregated domains.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] A central pore, which is enclosed between the TMDs, is slightly open towards the intracellular face with a gap between two domains allowing access of substrate from the lipid phase.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Substantial repacking and possible rotation of the TM helices upon nucleotide binding suggests a helix rotation model for the transport mechanism.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The genome of the model plant *Arabidopsis thaliana* is capable of encoding 120 ABC proteins compared to 50-70 ABC proteins that are encoded by the human genome and fruit flies (*Drosophila melanogaster*).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Plant ABC proteins are categorized in 13 subfamilies on the basis of size (full, half or quarter), orientation, and overall amino acid sequence similarity.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Multidrug resistant (MDR) homologs, also known as P-glycoproteins, represent the largest subfamily in plants with 22 members and the second largest overall ABC subfamily.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The B subfamily of plant ABC transporters (ABCBs) are characterized by their localization to the plasma membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Plant ABCB transporters are characterized by heterologously expressing them in *Escherichia coli*, *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*, *Schizosaccharomyces pombe* (fission yeast), and HeLa cells to determine substrate specificity.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Plant ABCB transporters have shown to transport the phytohormone indole-3-acetic acid ( IAA), also known as auxin, the essential regulator for plant growth and development.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The directional polar transport of auxin mediates plant environmental responses through processes such as phototropism and gravitropism.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The first high-resolution structure reported for an ABC exporter was that of Sav1866 (3.A.1.106.2) from *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Sav1866 is a homolog of multidrug ABC transporters.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It shows significant sequence similarity to human ABC transporters of subfamily B that includes MDR1 and TAP1/TAP2.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The ATPase activity of Sav1866 is known to be stimulated by cancer drugs such as doxorubicin, vinblastine and others, which suggests similar substrate specificity to P-glycoprotein and therefore a possible common mechanism of substrate translocation.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Sav1866 is a homodimer of half transporters, and each subunit contains an N-terminal TMD with six helices and a C-terminal NBD.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The NBDs are similar in structure to those of other ABC transporters, in which the two ATP binding sites are formed at the dimer interface between the Walker A motif of one NBD and the LSGGQ motif of the other.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The ADP-bound structure of Sav1866 shows the NBDs in a closed dimer and the TM helices split into two "wings" oriented towards the periplasm, forming the outward-facing conformation.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Each wing consists of helices TM1-2 from one subunit and TM3-6 from the other subunit.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It contains long intracellular loops (ICLs or ICD) connecting the TMDs that extend beyond the lipid bilayer into the cytoplasm and interacts with the 8=D.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Whereas the importers contain a short coupling helix that contact a single NBD, Sav1866 has two intracellular coupling helices, one (ICL1) contacting the NBDs of both subunits and the other (ICL2) interacting with only the opposite NBD subunit.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] MsbA (3.A.1.106.1) is a multi-drug resistant (MDR) ABC transporter and possibly a lipid flippase.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It is an ATPase that transports lipid A, the hydrophobic moiety of lipopolysaccharide (LPS), a glucosamine-based saccharolipid that makes up the outer monolayer of the outer membranes of most gram-negative bacteria.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Lipid A is an endotoxin and so loss of MsbA from the cell membrane or mutations that disrupt transport results in the accumulation of lipid A in the inner cell membrane resulting to cell death.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It is a close bacterial homolog of P-glycoprotein (Pgp) by protein sequence homology and has overlapping substrate specificities with the MDR-ABC transporter LmrA from *Lactococcus lactis*.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] MsbA from *E. coli* is 36% identical to the NH2-terminal half of human MDR1, suggesting a common mechanism for transport of amphiphatic and hydrophobic substrates.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The MsbA gene encodes a half transporter that contains a transmembrane domain (TMD) fused with a nucleotide-binding domain (NBD).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It is assembled as a homodimer with a total molecular mass of 129.2 kD.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] MsbA contains 6 TMDs on the periplasmic side, an NBD located on the cytoplasmic side of the cell membrane, and an intracellular domain (ICD), bridging the TMD and NBD.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This conserved helix extending from the TMD segments into or near the active site of the NBD is largely responsible for crosstalk between TMD and NBD.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In particular, ICD1 serves as a conserved pivot about which the NBD can rotate, therefore allowing the NBD to disassociate and dimerize during ATP binding and hydrolysis.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Previously published (and now retracted) X-ray structures of MsbA were inconsistent with the bacterial homolog Sav1866.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The structures were reexamined and found to have an error in the assignment of the hand resulting to incorrect models of MsbA.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Recently, the errors have been rectified and new structures have been reported.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The resting state of *E. coli* MsbA exhibits an inverted "V" shape with a chamber accessible to the interior of the transporter suggesting an *open, inward-facing conformation*.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The dimer contacts are concentrated between the extracellular loops and while the NBDs are ≈50Å apart, the subunits are facing each other.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The distance between the residues in the site of the dimer interface have been verified by cross-linking experiments and EPR spectroscopy studies.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The relatively large chamber allows it to accommodate large head groups such as that present in lipid A.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Significant conformational changes are required to move the large sugar head groups across the membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The difference between the two nucleotide-free (apo) structures is the ≈30° pivot of TM4/TM5 helices relative to the TM3/TM6 helices.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In the closed apo state (from *V. cholerae* MsbA), the NBDs are aligned and although closer, have not formed an ATP sandwich, and the P loops of opposing monomers are positioned next to one another.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In comparison to the open conformation, the dimer interface of the TMDs in the *closed, inward-facing conformation* has extensive contacts.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] For both apo conformations of MsbA, the chamber opening is facing inward.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The structure of MsbA-AMP-PNP (5'-adenylyl-β-γ-imidodiphosphate), obtained from *S. typhimurium*, is similar to Sav1866.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The NBDs in this *nucleotide-bound, outward-facing conformation*, come together to form a canonical ATP dimer sandwich, that is, the nucleotide is situated in between the P-loop and LSGGQ motif.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The conformational transition from MsbA-closed-apo to MsbA-AMP-PNP involves two steps, which are more likely concerted: a ≈10° pivot of TM4/TM5 helices towards TM3/TM6, bringing the NBDs closer but not into alignment followed by tilting of TM4/TM5 helices ≈20° out of plane.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The twisting motion results in the separation of TM3/TM6 helices away from TM1/TM2 leading to a change from an inward- to an outward- facing conformation.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Thus, changes in both the orientation and spacing of the NBDs dramatically rearrange the packing of transmembrane helices and effectively switch access to the chamber from the inner to the outer leaflet of the membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The structures determined for MsbA is basis for the tilting model of transport.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The structures described also highlight the dynamic nature of ABC exporters as also suggested by fluorescence and EPR studies.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Recent work has resulted in the discovery of MsbA inhibitors.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABC exporters have a transport mechanism that is consistent with both the alternating-access model and ATP-switch model.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In the apo states of exporters, the conformation is inward-facing and the TMDs and NBDs are relatively far apart to accommodate amphiphilic or hydrophobic substrates.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] For MsbA, in particular, the size of the chamber is large enough to accommodate the sugar groups from lipopolysaccharides (LPS).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] As has been suggested by several groups, binding of substrate initiates the transport cycle.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The "power stroke", that is, ATP binding that induces NBD dimerization and formation of the ATP sandwich, drives the conformational changes in the TMDs.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In MsbA, the sugar head groups are sequestered within the chamber during the "power stroke".
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The cavity is lined with charged and polar residues that are likely solvated creating an energetically unfavorable environment for hydrophobic substrates and energetically favorable for polar moieties in amphiphilic compounds or sugar groups from LPS.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Since the lipid cannot be stable for a long time in the chamber environment, lipid A and other hydrophobic molecules may "flip" into an energetically more favorable position within the outer membrane leaflet.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The "flipping" may also be driven by the rigid-body shearing of the TMDs while the hydrophobic tails of the LPS are dragged through the lipid bilayer.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Repacking of the helices switches the conformation into an outward-facing state.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ATP hydrolysis may widen the periplasmic opening and push the substrate towards the outer leaflet of the lipid bilayer.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Hydrolysis of the second ATP molecule and release of Pi separates the NBDs followed by restoration of the resting state, opening the chamber towards the cytoplasm for another cycle.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] ABC transporters are known to play a crucial role in the development of multidrug resistance (MDR).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In MDR, patients that are on medication eventually develop resistance not only to the drug they are taking but also to several different types of drugs.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This is caused by several factors, one of which is increased expulsion of the drug from the cell by ABC transporters.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] For example, the ABCB1 protein (P-glycoprotein) functions in pumping tumor suppression drugs out of the cell.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Pgp also called MDR1, ABCB1, is the prototype of ABC transporters and also the most extensively-studied gene.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Pgp is known to transport organic cationic or neutral compounds.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] A few ABCC family members, also known as MRP, have also been demonstrated to confer MDR to organic anion compounds.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The most-studied member in ABCG family is ABCG2, also known as BCRP (breast cancer resistance protein) confer resistance to most Topoisomerase I or II inhibitors such as topotecan, irinotecan, and doxorubicin.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] It is unclear exactly how these proteins can translocate such a wide variety of drugs, however, one model (the hydrophobic vacuum cleaner model) states that, in P-glycoprotein, the drugs are bound indiscriminately from the lipid phase based on their hydrophobicity.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The Discovery of the first eukaryotic ABC transporter protein came from studies on tumor cells and cultured cells that exhibited resistance to several drugs with unrelated chemical structures.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] These cells were shown to express elevated levels of multidrug-resistance (MDR) transport protein which was originally called P-glycoprotein (P-gp), but it is also referred to as multidrug resistance protein 1 (MDR1) or ABCB1.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This protein uses ATP hydrolysis, just like the other ABC transporters, to export a large variety of drugs from the cytosol to the extracellular medium.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In multidrug-resistant cells, the MDR1 gene is frequently amplified.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This results in a large overproduction of the MDR1 protein.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The substrates of mammalian ABCB1 are primarily planar, lipid-soluble molecules with one or more positive charges.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] All of these substrates compete with one another for transport, suggesting that they bind to the same or overlapping sites on the protein.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Many of the drugs that are transported out by ABCB1 are small, nonpolar drugs that diffuse across the extracellular medium into the cytosol, where they block various cellular functions.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Drugs such as colchicine and vinblastine, which block assembly of microtubules, freely cross the membrane into the cytosol, but the export of these drugs by ABCB1 reduces their concentration in the cell.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Therefore, it takes a higher concentration of the drugs is required to kill the cells that express ABCB1 than those that do not express the gene.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Other ABC transporters that contribute to multidrug resistance are ABCC1 (MRP1) and ABCG2 (breast cancer resistance protein).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] To solve the problems associated with multidrug-resistance by MDR1, different types of drugs can be used or the ABC transporters themselves must be inhibited.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] For other types of drugs to work, they must bypass the resistance mechanism, which is the ABC transporter.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] To do this other anticancer drugs can be utilized such as alkylating drugs (cyclophosphamide), antimetabolites (5-fluorouracil), and the anthracycline modified drugs (annamycin and doxorubicin-peptide).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] These drugs would not function as a substrate of ABC transporters, and would thus not be transported.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The other option is to use a combination of ABC inhibitory drugs and anticancer drugs at the same time.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] This would reverse the resistance to the anticancer drugs so that they could function as intended.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The substrates that reverse the resistance to anticancer drugs are called chemosensitizers.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Drug resistance is a common clinical problem that occurs in patients with infectious diseases and in patients with cancer.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Prokaryotic and eukaryotic microorganisms as well as neoplastic cells are often found to be resistant to drugs.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] MDR is frequently associated with overexpression of ABC transporters.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Inhibition of ABC transporters by low-molecular weight compounds has been extensively investigated in cancer patients; however, the clinical results have been disappointing.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] Recently various RNAi strategies have been applied to reverse MDR in different tumor models and this technology is effective in reversing ABC-transporter-mediated MDR in cancer cells and is therefore a promising strategy for overcoming MDR by gene therapeutic applications.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] RNAi technology could also be considered for overcoming MDR in infectious diseases caused by microbial pathogens.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] In addition to conferring MDR in tumor cells, ABC transporters are also expressed in the membranes of healthy cells, where they facilitate the transport of various endogenous substances, as well as of substances foreign to the body.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] For instance, ABC transporters such as Pgp, the MRPs and BCRP limit the absorption of many drugs from the intestine, and pump drugs from the liver cells to the bile as a means of removing foreign substances from the body.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] A large number of drugs are either transported by ABC transporters themselves or affect the transport of other drugs.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p01] The latter scenario can lead to drug-drug interactions, sometimes resulting in altered effects of the drugs.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] There are a number of assay types that allow the detection of ABC transporter interactions with endogenous and xenobiotic compounds.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The complexity of assay range from relatively simple membrane assays. like vesicular transport assay, ATPase assay to more complex cell based assays up to intricate *in vivo**Jeffrey P, Summerfield SG (2007).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] "Challenges for blood-brain barrier (BBB) screening".
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The *vesicular transport assay* detects the translocation of molecules by ABC transporters.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Membranes prepared under suitable conditions contain inside-out oriented vesicles with the ATP binding site and substrate binding site of the transporter facing the buffer outside.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Substrates of the transporter are taken up into the vesicles in an ATP dependent manner.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Rapid filtration using glass fiber filters or nitrocellulose membranes are used to separate the vesicles from the incubation solution and the test compound trapped inside the vesicles is retained on the filter.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The quantity of the transported unlabelled molecules is determined by HPLC, LC/MS, LC/MS/MS.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Alternatively, the compounds are radiolabeled, fluorescent or have a fluorescent tag so that the radioactivity or fluorescence retained on the filter can be quantified.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Various types of membranes from different sources (e.g. insect cells, transfected or selected mammalian cell lines) are used in vesicular transport studies.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Membranes are commercially available or can be prepared from various cells or even tissues e.g. liver canalicular membranes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] This assay type has the advantage of measuring the actual disposition of the substrate across the cell membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Its disadvantage is that compounds with medium-to-high passive permeability are not retained inside the vesicles making direct transport measurements with this class of compounds difficult to perform.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The vesicular transport assay can be performed in an "indirect" setting, where interacting test drugs modulate the transport rate of a reporter compound.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] This assay type is particularly suitable for the detection of possible drug-drug interactions and drug-endogenous substrate interactions.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] It is not sensitive to the passive permeability of the compounds and therefore detects all interacting compounds.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Yet, it does not provide information on whether the compound tested is an inhibitor of the transporter, or a substrate of the transporter inhibiting its function in a competitive fashion.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] A typical example of an indirect vesicular transport assay is the detection of the inhibition of taurocholate transport by ABCB11 (BSEP).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Efflux transporter-expressing cells actively pump substrates out of the cell, which results in a lower rate of substrate accumulation, lower intracellular concentration at steady state, or a faster rate of substrate elimination from cells loaded with the substrate.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Transported radioactive substrates or labeled fluorescent dyes can be directly measured, or in an indirect set up, the modulation of the accumulation of a probe substrate (e.g. fluorescent dyes like rhodamine 123, or calcein) can be determined in the presence of a test drug.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Calcein-AM, A highly permeable derivative of calcein readily penetrates into intact cells, where the endogenous esterases rapidly hydrolyze it to the fluorescent calcein.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] In contrast to calcein-AM, calcein has low permeability and therefore gets trapped in the cell and accumulates.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] As calcein-AM is an excellent substrate of the MDR1 and MRP1 efflux transporters, cells expressing MDR1 and/or MRP1 transporters pump the calcein-AM out of the cell before esterases can hydrolyze it.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] This results in a lower cellular accumulation rate of calcein.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The higher the MDR activity is in the cell membrane, the less Calcein is accumulated in the cytoplasm.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] In MDR-expressing cells, the addition of an MDR inhibitor or an MDR substrate in excess dramatically increases the rate of Calcein accumulation.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Activity of multidrug transporter is reflected by the difference between the amounts of dye accumulated in the presence and the absence of inhibitor.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Using selective inhibitors, transport activity of MDR1 and MRP1 can be easily distinguished.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] This assay can be used to screen drugs for transporter interactions, and also to quantify the MDR activity of cells.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The calcein assay is the proprietary assay of SOLVO Biotechnology.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] There are 49 known ABC transporters present in humans, which are classified into seven families by the Human Genome Organization.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] A full list of human ABC transporters can be found from.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The ABCA subfamily is composed of 12 full transporters split into two subgroups.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The first subgroup consists of seven genes that map to six different chromosomes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] These are ABCA1, ABCA2, ABCA3, and ABCA4, ABCA7, ABCA12, and ABCA13.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The other subgroup consists of ABCA5 and ABCA6 and ABCA8, ABCA9 and ABCA10.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] All of subgroup 2 is organized into a head to tail cluster of chromosomes on chromosome 17q24.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Genes in this second subgroup are distinguished from ABCA1-like genes by having 37-38 exons as opposed to the 50 exons in ABCA1.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The ABCA1 subgroup is implicated in the development of genetic diseases.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] In the recessive Tangier's disease, the ABCA1 protein is mutated.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Also, the ABCA4 maps to a region of chromosome 1p21 that contains the gene for Stargardt's disease.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] This gene is found to be highly expressed in rod photoreceptors and is mutated in Stargardt's disease, recessive retinitis pigmentism, and the majority of recessive cone-rod dystrophy.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The ABCB subfamily is composed of four full transporters and two half transporters.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] This is the only human subfamily to have both half and full types of transporters.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] ABCB1 was discovered as a protein overexpressed in certain drug resistant tumor cells.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] It is expressed primarily in the blood–brain barrier and liver and is thought to be involved in protecting cells from toxins.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Cells that overexpress this protein exhibit multi-drug resistance.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Subfamily ABCC contains thirteen members and nine of these transporters are referred to as the Multidrug Resistance Proteins (MRPs).
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The MRP proteins are found throughout nature and they mediate many important functions.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] They are known to be involved in ion transport, toxin secretion, and signal transduction.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Of the nine MRP proteins, four of them, MRP4, 5, 8, 9, (ABCC4, 5, 11, and 12), have a typical ABC structure with four domains, comprising two membrane spanning domains, with each spanning domain followed by a nucleotide binding domain.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The remaining 5 MRP's (MRP1, 2, 6, 7) (ABCC1, 2, 3, 6 and 10) are known as long MRPs and feature an additional fifth domain at their N terminus.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] CFTR, the transporter involved in the disease cystic fibrosis, is also considered part of this subfamily.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Cystic fibrosis occurs upon mutation and loss of function of CFTR.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The sulfonylurea receptors (SUR), involved in insulin secretion, neuronal function, and muscle function, are also part of this family of proteins.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Mutations in SUR proteins are a potential cause of Neonatal diabetes mellitus.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] SUR is also the binding site for drugs such as sulfonylureas and potassium-channel openers activators such as diazoxide.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The ABCD subfamily consists of four genes that encode half transporters expressed exclusively in the peroxisome.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] ABCD1 is responsible for the X-linked form of Adrenoleukodystrophy (ALD) which is a disease characterized by neurodegeneration and adrenal deficiency that typically is initiated in late childhood.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The cells of ALD patients feature accumulation of unbranched saturated fatty acids, but the exact role of ABCD1 in the process is still undetermined.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] In addition, the function of other ABCD genes have yet to be determined but have been thought to exert related functions in fatty acid metabolism.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Both of these subgroups are composed of genes that have ATP binding domains that are closely related to other ABC transporters, but these genes do not encode for trans-membrane domains.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] ABCE consists of only one member, OABP or ABCE1, which is known to recognize certain oligodendrocytes produced in response to certain viral infections.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Each member of the ABCF subgroup consist of a pair of ATP binding domains.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Six half transporters with ATP binding sites on the N terminus and trans-membrane domains at the C terminus make up the ABCG subfamily.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] This orientation is opposite of all other ABC genes.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] There are only 5 ABCG genes in the human genome, but there are 15 in the Drosophila genome and 10 in yeast.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The ABCG2 gene was discovered in cell lines selected for high level resistance for mitoxantrone and no expression of ABCB1 or ABCC1.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] ABCG2 can export anthracycline anticancer drugs, as well as topotecan, mitoxantrone, or doxorubicin as substrates.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Chromosomal translocations have been found to cause the ABCG2 amplification or rearrangement found in resistant cell lines.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The following classification system for transmembrane solute transporters has been constructed in the TCDB.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Three families of ABC exporters are defined by their evolutionary origins.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] ABC1 exporters evolved by intragenic triplication of a 2 TMS precursor (TMS = transmembrane segment.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] A "2 TMS" protein has 2 transmembrane segments) to give 6 TMS proteins.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] ABC2 exporters evolved by intragenic duplication of a 3 TMS precursor, and ABC3 exporters evolved from a 4 TMS precursor which duplicated either extragenicly to give two 4 TMS proteins, both required for transport function, or intragenicly to give 8 or 10 TMS proteins.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] The 10 TMS proteins appear to have two extra TMSs between the two 4 TMS repeat units.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Most uptake systems (all except 3.A.1.21) are of the ABC2 type, divided into type I and type II by the way they handle nucleotides.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] A special subfamily of ABC2 importers called ECF use a separate subunit for substrate recognition.
[src:active-transport/atp-binding-cassette-p02] Many structures of water-soluble domains of ABC proteins have been produced in recent years.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Anhydridic bonds are often labelled as "*high-energy bonds"*.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] P-O bonds are in fact fairly strong (~30 kJ/mol stronger than C-N bonds) and themselves not particularly easy to break.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] As noted below, energy is released by the hydrolysis of ATP.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] However, when the P-O bonds are broken, *input* of energy is required.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] It is the formation of new bonds and lower-energy inorganic phosphate with a *release of a larger amount of energy* that lowers the total energy of the system and makes it more stable.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Hydrolysis of the phosphate groups in ATP is especially exergonic, because the resulting inorganic phosphate molecular ion is greatly stabilized by multiple resonance structures, making the products (ADP and Pi) lower in energy than the reactant (ATP).
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] The high negative charge density associated with the three adjacent phosphate units of ATP also destabilizes the molecule, making it higher in energy.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Hydrolysis relieves some of these electrostatic repulsions, liberating useful energy in the process by causing conformational changes in enzyme structure.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] In humans, approximately 60 percent of the energy released from the hydrolysis of ATP produces metabolic heat rather than fuel the actual reactions taking place.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Due to the acid-base properties of ATP, ADP, and inorganic phosphate, the hydrolysis of ATP has the effect of lowering the pH of the reaction medium.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Under certain conditions, high levels of ATP hydrolysis can contribute to lactic acidosis.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Hydrolysis of the terminal phosphoanhydridic bond is a highly exergonic process.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] The amount of released energy depends on the conditions in a particular cell.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Specifically, the energy released is dependent on concentrations of ATP, ADP and Pi.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] As the concentrations of these molecules deviate from values at equilibrium, the value of Gibbs free energy change (Δ*G*) will be increasingly different.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] In standard conditions (ATP, ADP and Pi concentrations are equal to 1M, water concentration is equal to 55 M) the value of Δ*G* is between -28 and -34 kJ/mol.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] The range of the Δ*G* value exists because this reaction is dependent on the concentration of Mg2+ cations, which stabilize the ATP molecule.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] The cellular environment also contributes to differences in the Δ*G* value since ATP hydrolysis is dependent not only on the studied cell, but also on the surrounding tissue and even the compartment within the cell.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Variability in the Δ*G* values is therefore to be expected.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] The relationship between the standard Gibbs free energy change Δr*G*o and chemical equilibrium is revealing.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] This relationship is defined by the equation Δr*G*o = -*RT* ln(*K*), where *K* is the equilibrium constant, which is equal to the reaction quotient *Q* in equilibrium.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] The standard value of Δ*G* for this reaction is, as mentioned, between -28 and -34 kJ/mol; however, experimentally determined concentrations of the involved molecules reveal that the reaction is not at equilibrium.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Given this fact, a comparison between the equilibrium constant, *K*, and the reaction quotient, *Q*, provides insight.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] *K* takes into consideration reactions taking place in standard conditions, but in the cellular environment the concentrations of the involved molecules (namely, ATP, ADP, and Pi) are far from the standard 1 M.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] In fact, the concentrations are more appropriately measured in mM, which is smaller than M by three orders of magnitude.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Using these nonstandard concentrations, the calculated value of *Q* is much less than one.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] By relating *Q* to Δ*G* using the equation Δ*G* = Δr*G*o + *RT* ln(*Q*), where Δr*G*o is the standard change in Gibbs free energy for the hydrolysis of ATP, it is found that the magnitude of Δ*G* is much greater than the standard value.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] The nonstandard conditions of the cell actually result in a more favorable reaction.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] In one particular study, to determine Δ*G* in vivo in humans, the concentration of ATP, ADP, and Pi was measured using nuclear magnetic resonance.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] In human muscle cells at rest, the concentration of ATP was found to be around 4 mM and the concentration of ADP was around 9 μM.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Inputing these values into the above equations yields Δ*G* = -64 kJ/mol.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] After ischemia, when the muscle is recovering from exercise, the concentration of ATP is as low as 1 mM and the concentration of ADP is around 7 μM.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] Therefore, the absolute Δ*G* would be as high as -69 kJ/mol.
[src:active-transport/atp-hydrolysis] By comparing the standard value of Δ*G* and the experimental value of Δ*G*, one can see that the energy released from the hydrolysis of ATP, as measured in humans, is almost twice as much as the energy produced under standard conditions.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] ATP synthase lies across a cellular membrane and forms an aperture that protons can cross from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration, imparting energy for the synthesis of ATP.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] This electrochemical gradient is generated by the electron transport chain and allows cells to store energy in ATP for later use.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] In prokaryotic cells ATP synthase lies across the plasma membrane, while in eukaryotic cells it lies across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Organisms capable of photosynthesis also have ATP synthase across the thylakoid membrane, which in plants is located in the chloroplast and in cyanobacteria is located in the cytoplasm.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] ATP synthase is present in all organisms studied.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Eukaryotic ATP synthases are F-ATPases (which usually work as ATP synthases instead of ATPases in cellular environments) and running "in reverse" for an ATPase (ATPases catalyze the decomposition of ATP into ADP and a free phosphate ion).
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] This article deals mainly with this type.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] An F-ATPase consists of two main subunits, FO and F1, which has a rotational motor mechanism allowing for ATP production.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The F1 fraction derives its name from the term "Fraction 1" and FO (written as a subscript letter "o", not "zero") derives its name from being the binding fraction for oligomycin, a type of naturally derived antibiotic that is able to inhibit the FO unit of ATP synthase.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] These functional regions consist of different protein subunits — refer to tables.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] This enzyme is used in synthesis of ATP through aerobic respiration.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Located within the thylakoid membrane and the inner mitochondrial membrane, ATP synthase consists of two regions FO and F1.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] FO causes rotation of F1 and is made of c-ring and subunits a, two b, F6.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] F1 has a water-soluble part that can hydrolyze ATP.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] FO on the other hand has mainly hydrophobic regions.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] FO F1 creates a pathway for protons movement across the membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The F1 portion of ATP synthase is hydrophilic and responsible for hydrolyzing ATP.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The F1 unit protrudes into the cytoplasm (matrix and stroma in mitochondria and chloroplasts respectively).
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Subunits α and β make a hexamer with 6 binding sites.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Three of them are catalytically inactive and they bind ADP.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Three other subunits catalyze the ATP synthesis.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The other F1 subunits γ, δ, and ε are a part of a rotational motor mechanism (rotor/axle).
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The γ subunit allows β to go through conformational changes (i.e., closed, half open, and open states) that allow for ATP to be bound and released once synthesized.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The F1 particle is large and can be seen in the transmission electron microscope by negative staining.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] These are particles of 9 nm diameter that pepper the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] FO is a water insoluble protein with eight subunits and a transmembrane ring.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The FO region of ATP synthase is a proton pore that is embedded in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] It consists of three main subunits, a, b, and c.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Six c subunits make up the rotor ring, and subunit b makes up a stalk connecting to F1 OSCP that prevents the αβ hexamer from rotating.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Humans have six additional subunits, d, e, f, g, F6, and 8 (or A6L).
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] This part of the enzyme is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and couples proton translocation to the rotation that causes ATP synthesis in the F1 region.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] In eukaryotes, mitochondrial FO forms membrane-bending dimers.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] These dimers self-arrange into long rows at the end of the cristae, possibly the first step of cristae formation.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] An atomic model for the dimeric yeast FO region was determined by cryo-EM at an overall resolution of 3.6 Å.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] In the 1960s through the 1970s, Paul Boyer, a UCLA Professor, developed the binding change, or flip-flop, mechanism theory, which postulated that ATP synthesis is dependent on a conformational change in ATP synthase generated by rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Walker, then at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge, crystallized the F1 catalytic-domain of ATP synthase.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The structure, at the time the largest asymmetric protein structure known, indicated that Boyer's rotary-catalysis model was, in essence, correct.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] For elucidating this, Boyer and Walker shared half of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The crystal structure of the F1 showed alternating alpha and beta subunits (3 of each), arranged like segments of an orange around a rotating asymmetrical gamma subunit.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] A portion of the FO (the ring of c-subunits) rotates as the protons pass through the membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The c-ring is tightly attached to the asymmetric central stalk (consisting primarily of the gamma subunit), causing it to rotate within the alpha3beta3 of F1 causing the 3 catalytic nucleotide binding sites to go through a series of conformational changes that lead to ATP synthesis.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The major F1 subunits are prevented from rotating in sympathy with the central stalk rotor by a peripheral stalk that joins the alpha3beta3 to the non-rotating portion of FO.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The structure of the intact ATP synthase is currently known at low-resolution from electron cryo-microscopy (cryo-EM) studies of the complex.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The cryo-EM model of ATP synthase suggests that the peripheral stalk is a flexible structure that wraps around the complex as it joins F1 to FO.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Under the right conditions, the enzyme reaction can also be carried out in reverse, with ATP hydrolysis driving proton pumping across the membrane.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The binding change mechanism involves the active site of a β subunit's cycling between three states.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] In the "loose" state, ADP and phosphate enter the active site; in the adjacent diagram, this is shown in pink.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The enzyme then undergoes a change in shape and forces these molecules together, with the active site in the resulting "tight" state (shown in red) binding the newly produced ATP molecule with very high affinity.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Finally, the active site cycles back to the open state (orange), releasing ATP and binding more ADP and phosphate, ready for the next cycle of ATP production.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Like other enzymes, the activity of F1FO ATP synthase is reversible.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Large-enough quantities of ATP cause it to create a transmembrane proton gradient, this is used by fermenting bacteria that do not have an electron transport chain, but rather hydrolyze ATP to make a proton gradient, which they use to drive flagella and the transport of nutrients into the cell.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] In respiring bacteria under physiological conditions, ATP synthase, in general, runs in the opposite direction, creating ATP while using the proton motive force created by the electron transport chain as a source of energy.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The overall process of creating energy in this fashion is termed oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The same process takes place in the mitochondria, where ATP synthase is located in the inner mitochondrial membrane and the F1-part projects into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] By pumping proton cations into the matrix, the ATP-synthase converts ADP into ATP.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The evolution of ATP synthase is thought to have been modular whereby two functionally independent subunits became associated and gained new functionality.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] This association appears to have occurred early in evolutionary history, because essentially the same structure and activity of ATP synthase enzymes are present in all kingdoms of life.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The F-ATP synthase displays high functional and mechanistic similarity to the V-ATPase.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] However, whereas the F-ATP synthase generates ATP by utilising a proton gradient, the V-ATPase generates a proton gradient at the expense of ATP, generating pH values of as low as 1.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The F1 region also shows significant similarity to hexameric DNA helicases (especially the Rho factor), and the entire enzyme region shows some similarity to H+ -powered T3SS or flagellar motor complexes.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The α3β3 hexamer of the F1 region shows significant structural similarity to hexameric DNA helicases; both form a ring with 3-fold rotational symmetry with a central pore.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The H+ motor of the FO particle shows great functional similarity to the H+ motors that drive flagella.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Both feature a ring of many small alpha-helical proteins that rotate relative to nearby stationary proteins, using a H+ potential gradient as an energy source.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] This link is tenuous, however, as the overall structure of flagellar motors is far more complex than that of the FO particle and the ring with about 30 rotating proteins is far larger than the 10, 11, or 14 helical proteins in the FO complex.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] More recent structural data do however show that the ring and the stalk are structurally similar to the F1 particle.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The modular evolution theory for the origin of ATP synthase suggests that two subunits with independent function, a DNA helicase with ATPase activity and a H+ motor, were able to bind, and the rotation of the motor drove the ATPase activity of the helicase in reverse.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] This complex then evolved greater efficiency and eventually developed into today's intricate ATP synthases.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Alternatively, the DNA helicase/H+ motor complex may have had H+ pump activity with the ATPase activity of the helicase driving the H+ motor in reverse.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] This may have evolved to carry out the reverse reaction and act as an ATP synthase.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] A variety of natural and synthetic inhibitors of ATP synthase have been discovered.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] These have been used to probe the structure and mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] There are several classes of ATP synthase inhibitors, including peptide inhibitors, polyphenolic phytochemicals, polyketides, organotin compounds, polyenic α-pyrone derivatives, cationic inhibitors, substrate analogs, amino acid modifiers, and other miscellaneous chemicals.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Some of the most commonly used ATP synthase inhibitors are oligomycin and DCCD.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Bacterial F-ATPases can occasionally operate in reverse, turning them into an ATPase.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Some bacteria have no F-ATPase, using an A/V-type ATPase bidirectionally.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Yeast ATP synthase is one of the best-studied eukaryotic ATP synthases; and five F1, eight FO subunits, and seven associated proteins have been identified.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Most of these proteins have homologues in other eukaryotes.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] In plants, ATP synthase is also present in chloroplasts (CF1FO-ATP synthase).
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The enzyme is integrated into thylakoid membrane; the CF1-part sticks into stroma, where dark reactions of photosynthesis (also called the light-independent reactions or the Calvin cycle) and ATP synthesis take place.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The overall structure and the catalytic mechanism of the chloroplast ATP synthase are almost the same as those of the bacterial enzyme.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] However, in chloroplasts, the proton motive force is generated not by respiratory electron transport chain but by primary photosynthetic proteins.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The synthase has a 40-aa insert in the gamma-subunit to inhibit wasteful activity when dark.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The ATP synthase isolated from bovine (*Bos taurus*) heart mitochondria is, in terms of biochemistry and structure, the best-characterized ATP synthase.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Beef heart is used as a source for the enzyme because of the high concentration of mitochondria in cardiac muscle.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Their genes have close homology to human ATP synthases.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Eukaryotes belonging to some divergent lineages have very special organizations of the ATP synthase.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] A euglenozoa ATP synthase forms a dimer with a boomerang-shaped F1 head like other mitochondrial ATP synthases, but the FO subcomplex has many unique subunits.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] The inhibitory IF1 also binds differently, in a way shared with trypanosomatida.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Apicomplexans, such as *Plasmodium*, utilise a hexameric ATP synthase organisation existing as a trimer of ATP synthase dimers.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] These hexameric assemblies arrange into pentagonal pyramids, which induce a unique bulbous cristae membrane morphology.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] This organisation is underpinned by both apicomplexan-specific subunits and cardiolipins.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Archaea do not generally have an F-ATPase.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Instead, they synthesize ATP using the A-ATPase/synthase, a rotary machine structurally similar to the V-ATPase but mainly functioning as an ATP synthase.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] Like the bacteria F-ATPase, it is believed to also function as an ATPase.
[src:active-transport/atp-synthase] F-ATPase gene linkage and gene order are widely conserved across ancient prokaryote lineages, implying that this system already existed at a date before the last universal common ancestor, the LUCA.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Some such enzymes are integral membrane proteins (anchored within biological membranes), and move solutes across the membrane, typically against their concentration gradient.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Transmembrane ATPases import metabolites necessary for cell metabolism and export toxins, wastes, and solutes that can hinder cellular processes.
[src:active-transport/atpase] An important example is the sodium-potassium pump (Na+/K+ATPase) that maintains the cell membrane potential.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Another example is the hydrogen potassium ATPase (H+/K+ATPase or gastric proton pump) that acidifies the contents of the stomach.
[src:active-transport/atpase] ATPase is genetically conserved in animals; therefore, cardenolides which are toxic steroids produced by plants that act on ATPases, make general and effective animal toxins that act dose dependently.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Besides exchangers, other categories of transmembrane ATPase include co-transporters and pumps (however, some exchangers are also pumps).
[src:active-transport/atpase] Some of these, like the Na+/K+ATPase, cause a net flow of charge, but others do not.
[src:active-transport/atpase] These are called electrogenic transporters and electroneutral transporters, respectively.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Genetic variants in ATPases result in a wide spectrum of human diseases, from prenatal to later onset disease.
[src:active-transport/atpase] The Walker motifs are a telltale protein sequence motif for nucleotide binding and hydrolysis.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Beyond this broad function, the Walker motifs can be found in almost all natural ATPases, with the notable exception of tyrosine kinases.
[src:active-transport/atpase] The Walker motifs commonly form a Beta sheet-turn-Alpha helix that is self-organized as a Nest (protein structural motif).
[src:active-transport/atpase] This is thought to be because modern ATPases evolved from small NTP-binding peptides that had to be self-organized.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Protein design has been able to replicate the ATPase function (weakly) without using natural ATPase sequences or structures.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Importantly, while all natural ATPases have some beta-sheet structure, the designed "Alternative ATPase" lacks beta sheet structure, demonstrating that this life-essential function is possible with sequences and structures not found in nature.
[src:active-transport/atpase] ATPase (also called FoF1-ATP Synthase) is a charge-transferring complex that catalyzes ATP to perform ATP synthesis by moving ions through the membrane.
[src:active-transport/atpase] The coupling of ATP hydrolysis and transport is a chemical reaction in which a fixed number of solute molecules are transported for each ATP molecule hydrolyzed; for the Na+/K+ exchanger, this is three Na+ ions out of the cell and two K+ ions inside per ATP molecule hydrolyzed.
[src:active-transport/atpase] This process is referred to as active transport.
[src:active-transport/atpase] For instance, inhibiting vesicular H+-ATPases would result in a rise in the pH within vesicles and a drop in the pH of the cytoplasm.
[src:active-transport/atpase] All of the ATPases share a common basic structure.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Each rotary ATPase is composed of two major components: Fo/A0/V0 and F1/A1/V1.
[src:active-transport/atpase] They are connected by 1-3 stalks to maintain stability, control rotation, and prevent them from rotating in the other direction.
[src:active-transport/atpase] One stalk is utilized to transmit torque.
[src:active-transport/atpase] The number of peripheral stalks is dependent on the type of ATPase: F-ATPases have one, A-ATPases have two, and V-ATPases have three.
[src:active-transport/atpase] The F1 catalytic domain is located on the N-side (negative-side) of the membrane and is involved in the synthesis and degradation of ATP and is involved in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:active-transport/atpase] The Fo transmembrane domain is involved in the movement of ions across the membrane.
[src:active-transport/atpase] The bacterial FoF1-ATPase consists of the soluble F1 domain and the transmembrane Fo domain, which is composed of several subunits with varying stoichiometry.
[src:active-transport/atpase] There are two subunits, γ, and ε, that form the central stalk and they are linked to Fo.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Fo contains a c-subunit oligomer in the shape of a ring (c-ring).
[src:active-transport/atpase] The α subunit is close to the subunit b2 and makes up the stalk that connects the transmembrane subunits to the α3β3 and δ subunits.
[src:active-transport/atpase] F-ATP synthases are identical in appearance and function except for the mitochondrial FoF1-ATP synthase, which contains 7-9 additional subunits.
[src:active-transport/atpase] The electrochemical potential is what causes the c-ring to rotate in a clockwise direction for ATP synthesis.
[src:active-transport/atpase] This causes the central stalk and the catalytic domain to change shape.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Rotating the c-ring causes three ATP molecules to be made, which then causes H+ to move from the P-side (positive-side) of the membrane to the N-side (negative-side) of the membrane.
[src:active-transport/atpase] The counterclockwise rotation of the c-ring is driven by ATP hydrolysis and ions move from the N-side to the P-side, which helps to build up electrochemical potential.
[src:active-transport/atpase] The ATP synthase of mitochondria and chloroplasts is an anabolic enzyme that harnesses the energy of a transmembrane proton gradient as an energy source for adding an inorganic phosphate group to a molecule of adenosine diphosphate (ADP) to form a molecule of adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:active-transport/atpase] This enzyme works when a proton moves down the concentration gradient, giving the enzyme a spinning motion.
[src:active-transport/atpase] This unique spinning motion bonds ADP and P together to create ATP.
[src:active-transport/atpase] ATP synthase can also function in reverse, that is, use energy released by ATP hydrolysis to pump protons against their electrochemical gradient.
[src:active-transport/atpase] There are different types of ATPases, which can differ in function (ATP synthesis and/or hydrolysis), structure (F-, V- and A-ATPases contain rotary motors) and in the type of ions they transport.
[src:active-transport/atpase] P-ATPases (sometime known as E1-E2 ATPases) are found in bacteria and also in eukaryotic plasma membranes and organelles.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Its name is due to short time attachment of inorganic phosphate at the aspartate residues at the time of activation.
[src:active-transport/atpase] Function of P-ATPase is to transport a variety of different compounds, like ions and phospholipids, across a membrane using ATP hydrolysis for energy.
[src:active-transport/atpase] There are many different classes of P-ATPases, which transports a specific type of ion.
[src:active-transport/atpase] P-ATPases may be composed of one or two polypeptides, and can usually take two main conformations, E1 and E2.
